"Sunoji Dulhan" is a well-loved song from the Bollywood movie "Hum Saath-Saath Hain," released in 1999. Produced and directed by Sooraj R. Barjatya, the film is a family drama that features an ensemble cast, including Salman Khan, Mohnish Bahl, Tabu, Sonali Bendre, Karisma Kapoor, and Saif Ali Khan. The song "Sunoji Dulhan" epitomizes the convivial spirit of Indian weddings. It is a humorous and lively number performed during a sequence in the film where the family gathers together to give playful advice to the new bride as part of the wedding celebrations. Sung by a group of playback singers including Udit Narayan, Sonu Nigam, Kavita Krishnamurthy, and Roop Kumar Rathod, the song showcases the lighthearted teasing that often takes place in Indian weddings. The music and the lyrics of the song create a festive atmosphere that depicts the bonding of a joint family. A fun and interesting fact about the movie "Hum Saath-Saath Hain" is that it uses the age-old Indian tradition of a joint family system to convey its storytelling, which became a defining feature of the film and resonated strongly with the audience. The movie was a massive box office success, celebrated for its depiction of familial bonds and values, a trademark characteristic of Sooraj Barjatya's films. Additionally, another interesting aspect is that the intricate wardrobes and set decorations in the film, especially during the song sequences like "Sunoji Dulhan," required significant attention to detail and coordination to reflect the grand Indian wedding spirit authentically. . The song "Do Anjaane Ajnabi" is a romantic track from the 2006 Bollywood film "Vivah," which was written and directed by Sooraj R. Barjatya. The movie is known for its portrayal of the journey from engagement to marriage, following the lead characters played by Shahid Kapoor and Amrita Rao. "Do Anjaane Ajnabi" is beautifully sung by Udit Narayan and Shreya Ghoshal, with music composed by Ravindra Jain. The song captures the initial shyness and gradual connection that develops between the characters who are in an arranged marriage setup, as they embark on the path of getting to know one another and falling in love. An interesting fun fact about the movie "Vivah" is that it was the first Indian film to be released simultaneously in cinema and on the internet (through the production company's official website). This pioneering distribution model made it one of the most accessible films at the time. The movie's soundtrack, including songs like "Do Anjaane Ajnabi," contributed to its success and helped make "Vivah" a beloved film. The on-screen chemistry of Shahid Kapoor and Amrita Rao, complimented by the melodious music, left a lasting impression on audiences. . Vibhuti narayan mishra coreüéÄ . . Ingredients: some boiled arvi (around 300g) 2 medium onions 2 tomatoes 1-2 green chillies oil (for cooking + frying arvi) salt ‚Äì as per taste coriander powder red chilli powder kashmiri red chilli haldi garam masala a little kasuri methi fresh coriander Recipe: 1. Boil the Arvi in a pressure cooker for 2 whistles. Let them cool completely, then peel them. 2. Roughly chop onion, tomato, and green chili. Grind them together into a coarse paste. 3. Heat oil in a pan, add the paste, and cook till the masala releases oil. 4. Add salt, coriander powder, red chili powder, Kashmiri chili, turmeric, and garam masala. Mix well. 5. Add a splash of water to avoid burning and add crushed kasuri methi. Let the masala cook. 6. In the meantime, peel and fry arvi until golden brown. 7. Add fried arvi to the masala, pour in some water based on how thick you want the gravy. 8. Simmer for 5-7 minutes till everything blends beautifully. 9. Garnish with fresh coriander and serve hot with roti or rice! ü´∂ . . . #instagram #explore #viral #foryoupage #wife #dinner #corporate #corporategirl #corporatelife #viralvideos #instagood #pov #fypppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppppp #delhiuniversity #marriagegoals
